I think you misunderstand the purpose of method [getArray][1]. Some DBMSs, like Oracle, have [&quot;array&quot; data types][2]. Hence the `getArray` method &amp;ndash; to query a database table column whose type is an array type. I have no experience with MySQL but it appears that [it does not have an array type][3]. Hence the JDBC driver for MySQL does not need to implement the `getArray` method and that&#39;s why you get the `SQLFeatureNotSupportedException`.

You need to iterate through the `ResultSet` and build up your array. However since you usually don&#39;t know how many rows there are in a `ResultSet`, I usually use a `List` and then, if required, convert it to an array because when you declare an array you need to know its size.

I would also define a [record][4] and declare a `List` of records.  
(Note that below code is not compiled and not tested since I don&#39;t have your database and I can&#39;t simulate it since the code in your question is not a [minimal, reproducible example][5].)
```java
public record NameAndCountry(String name, String location) {
    public static java.util.List&lt;NameAndCountry&gt; retrieveNameAndLocation() {
        final String table = &quot;customers&quot;;
        try {
            ResultSet resultSet = statement.executeQuery(
                &quot;SELECT &quot; +
                    &quot;first_name,&quot; +
                    &quot;location&quot; +
                &quot; FROM &quot; + table
            );
            java.util.List&lt;NameAndCountry&gt; list = new java.util.ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
            while (resultSet.next()) {
                String name = resultSet.getString(1);
                String location = resultSet.getString(2);
                NameAndCountry row = new NameAndCountry(name, location);
                list.add(row);
            }
        } catch (SQLException  e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
        return list;
    }
}
```


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.sql/java/sql/ResultSet.html#getArray(int)
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/database/oracle/oracle-database/21/adobj/support-for-collection-data-types.html#GUID-0EF7C6B0-B68A-4671-A7B6-857D8F6F3DA8
  [3]: https://sebhastian.com/mysql-array/
  [4]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/14/language/records.html
  [5]: https://stackoverflow.com/help/minimal-reproducible-example

