answers.body_markdown:
You don&#39;t have to mock the **class** or the **method** you want to test. The idea behind mocking is to **mock** your dependencies. Here in your case, the class you want to test is `MainController` and it depends on `AnotherServiceImpl`. It is ok, you have mocked your dependency, so you don&#39;t have to mock `MainController`.

Also, here you are doing an *integration test* because of the annotation `@SpringBootTest` that will load all your context. And I guess this is not what you want when using `MockMvc`. You have to use [test slice][1] instead with the annotation `@WebMvcTest(MainController.class)`.

Your class should look something like that:

    @WebMvcTest(TestMainController.class)
    public class TestMainController {
        
        @MockBean
        AnotherServiceImpl anotherService;
    
        @Autowired
        private MockMvc mockMvc;
    
        @Before
        public void setup() {
            mockMvc = MockMvcBuilders.standaloneSetup(mainController).build();
        }
    
        @Test
        public void TestFirstFunctionFor201() throws Exception {
            String req = &quot;&lt;JSON_STRING&gt;&quot;;
            when(anotherService.someFunction(Mockito.anyString())).thenReturn(&quot;Success&quot;);
            this.mockMvc.perform(put(&quot;/Main/one/&quot;).contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
                    .content(req)).andExpect(status().isCreated());
        }
    }


  [1]: https://developer.okta.com/blog/2021/07/12/spring-boot-test-slices

